ava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Coggeshall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Middlesex): habitational name from Coggeshall in Essex, named from an Old English personal name <i>Cogg</i> + <i>halh</i> ‘nook’.","History: This name was taken to America in 1632 by John Coggeshall, who became first governor of RI, and in 1635 by John Cogswell. In 1887 a descendant, Daniel Cogswell, founded Cogswell College, San Francisco."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Coggeshall was born about 1279, in Coggeshall, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John de Coggeshall I, of Benfleet, was 26 and his mother, Sarah Plumbergh, was 21. He married Sara le Brun about 1301, in Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1319, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"Abt 1279–Abt 1319":"umbes 1279–umbes 1319","1279–1319":"1279–1319","1280–1319":"1280–1319","1283–Female":"1283–Surnud","1301–1361":"1301–1361","1301–1348":"1301–1348","1255–1296":"1255–1296","1260–1305":"1260–1305","Aft 1301":"pärast 1301","1296":"1296","1361":"1361","Abt 1279":"umbes 1279","Abt 1301":"umbes 1301","1283":"1283","Abt 1319":"umbes 1319","1260":"1260","before 1319":"enne 1319","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1301":"1301","1279":"1279","1255":"1255","about 1301":"